Diagnosis: Males differ from those of
C. concolor
by the morphology of the tibial apophysis (
Figs. 13– 14
) and palpal bulb (
Figs. 15–17
) and from those of
C. olivaceum
by the retrolateral branch of tibial apophysis being narrower, shorter and bearing 10 spines or fewer (
Figs. 13–14
). Females are distinguished by spermathecal morphology which comprise two very long, thin receptacula surmounted by a single terminal lobe (
Fig. 18
).
